<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-06T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-06T20:00:00-05:00" n="262" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d262">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/4004 Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in Switzerland (<persName corresp="#p_WHR1" type="to">Wilson</persName>), at Geneva</hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-06T20:00:00-05:00">February 6, 1932—8
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>6. Your No. 9, February 6, 1 p.m. With regard to my views on question of
                            the course which may best be pursued in the light of the Japanese reply
                            to the suggestions advanced by the American and other governments, it is
                            suggested that you inquire of <persName corresp="#p_SSJ1">Sir John
                                Simon</persName>.</p>
                        <p>For your confidential information, he is aware of my views and you may
                            inform him that I have so informed you.</p>
                        <p>The foregoing is confidential to you and to <persName corresp="#p_SSJ1">Sir John Simon</persName>.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_SHL1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>